<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911004-0070</DOCNO><DOCID>911004-0070.</DOCID><HL>   Law:   Former Drexel Broker Gets   One-Year Prison Sentence</HL><DATE>10/04/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)INSIDER TRADING (ISD)LAW andamp; LEGAL ISSUES AND LEGISLATION (LAW)</NS><GV>INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE (IRS)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>GEORGIA (GA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   ATLANTA -- A former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.stockbroker was sentenced to one year in prison and orderedto make restitution of $2 million to investors whom sheadmitted defrauding.   Karen L. Scherm, of Atlanta, pleaded guilty in June to thefraud scheme, which ran from March 1986 to June 1988. Sheadmitted soliciting funds from more than a dozen clients,after assuring them that their investments would beguaranteed and would have little or no risk. She spent themoney on herself and friends, prosecutors said.</LP><TEXT>   Joe D. Whitley, U.S. Attorney in Atlanta, said Ms. Schermwas the only defendant in the case and that no additionalcharges are expected. He said the scheme was unrelated toprevious cases involving Drexel or its employees.   In federal court here, Ms. Scherm was also ordered toserve three years' probation after her release from prison,and to provide 500 hours of community service. She was barredfrom again working in the securities or commodities industry.   Ms. Scherm was also directed to cooperate with theInternal Revenue Service's investigation to determine whethershe owes back taxes and penalties.</TEXT></DOC>